Jubilee Day; Landis, Heydler, August Herrmann (Reds prez) attending.  Six brass bands, 3000 kids in the crowd. Old-timers introduced to the crowd: Long John Riley, Dobby Mitchell (first curve ball pitcher), George Miller (Mitchell's catcher), Heinie Peitz, Bob Ewing, Algy McBride, Dummy Hoy, Jack Sudhoff, Jesse Tannehill, Charley Sweasey, Still Bill Hill, and last and oldest of all, Charley Keith of the famous Live Oaks of 1866.
Rolled clear to the flagstaff.  Bressler was almost to the plate before Brown could retrieve it.
Zach Wheat was officially installed as BRO manager before today's game.

CIN argued strenuously with Ump Sweeney; pop bottles were thrown out of the stands toward Sweeney.  A squad of police appeared on the field at the RF bleachers where the tossers were parked and the throwing ceased. Big crowd surrounded the field; ground rules held long pokes to doubles and triples.  Fans crowded on the roof of the grandstand and all the windows in the surrounding factories were filled.
Youngs argued with Ump O'Day; when he got back to the bench he tossed a handful of drinking cups at the ump but O'Day did not see them.
